entists alike how to improve the clarity, cogency, and communicative power of their words and images. In this remarkable guide, Joseph E. Harmon and Alan G. Gross have combined their many years of experience in the art of science writing to analyze published examples of how the best scientists communicate. Organized topically with information on the structural elements and the style of scientific communications, each chapter draws on models of past successes and failures to show students and practitioners how best to negotiate the world of print, online publication, and oral presentation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ascience writing, communication, composition, scholarship, research, publication, argument, conclusion, methods, article, conferences, powerpoint, slides, oral presentation, revision, editing, grant proposal, funding, handbook, manual, guidebook, reference, nonfiction, academia, faculty, graduate school, tenure, organization, clarity, technical terms.1 aGross, Alan G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022631661140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226316635423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226316635/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles